07/20/2022,748.1101(b)(3)(E) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,09/22/2022,09/16/2022,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium,Yes,Based on information gathered through the course of the investigation it has been determined that children are not always being granted privacy when trying to make phone calls with their CPS worker or CASAs. ,"Administrator sent the following plan. 
This message was sent out over TEAMS tagging all staff, so they are notified to read it.  This is our corrective action for Investigation 2911447.
September 15, 2022  Investigation 2911447 
We received a deficiency in: 
§748.1101. What rights does a child in care have? 
(b) The following categories include the childs rights that you must adhere to: 
(3) Living a normal life, including: 
(E) The right to privacy, including sending and receiving unopened mail, making and receiving phone calls, keeping a personal journal, and having visitors, unless the childs best interest, appropriate professionals, or court order necessitates restrictions [Medium]; 
All Staff please get with your Supervisors to discuss how to properly Monitor phone calls.  This standard has an exception included in it, unless the childs best interest, appropriate professionals, or court order necessitates restrictions.  Many of our kids have restrictions.  But, calls to Caseworkers and CASAs are never included in those restrictions.  Even if a CASA has a history of telling kids things like, Your Mothers Cancer is getting worse or Your mother will probably loose her rights in court in two weeks, and not telling us they have said this to the kid so we can offer him support or be prepared when the kid becomes exceptionally emotional and maybe violent, even then we are not allowed to listen in on the call.   
"
